english:
  title: 'On Gathering and Parting: A Farewell Verse for Lee Saseong'
  author: Kim Ilson
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In human life, gathering and parting—are these mere accidents? There must be something that brings us together, something that tears us apart. I know that these comings and goings stir our sorrows and joys, yet I cannot fathom what force orchestrates them all. When we gather, warmth suffuses our hearts; when we part, sudden desolation descends. They orchestrate the gathering and scattering, yet I am the one who rejoices and grieves. What heart is this sorrow and joy? It is not the gathering and parting alone that makes us sad or glad—in each person, in each heart, the sadness and gladness differ. Thus the sorrowful think of the joyful, and the joyful think of the sorrowful. After parting, we recall the time of gathering, and our hearts cannot find rest.

    This autumn, four of us came together at leisure: Shin Gaeji of Goryeong, Kang Saho of Jinyang, Lee Saseong of Anak, and myself. We were like a school of fish swimming as one. We ate from the same table, slept under the same blanket, walked in each other's shadow, sat facing one another. When we found delight, we recited together; when we found words, we sang together. Though our speech differed, our hearts were one. Though our steps did not mirror each other, our direction was the same. Our service to the state came at different times, yet our hours were the same. Our duties varied in scope, yet our work was as one. Day and night we dwelt together—our gathering reached its fullness.

    During that gathering, all was harmonious and warm. Looking outward, we were officials of the court; looking inward, we were humble scholars nourished by sacred virtue, awakened to heaven's truth. Four people became as one body in the grand harmony of heaven and earth. Soon Saseong departed to serve his parents in Daebang, bringing joy to him but sorrow to the three of us. Scarcely had he returned when the Ministry of Personnel, claiming urgent business, took Gaeji away. All four of us grieved. Then Saho went to Jinju to honor his parents—joy for him, sorrow for Saseong and me. Then came news that Saseong's father had fallen from favor, and he rushed home to comfort him. Now both Saseong and I grieved together.

    Now one of us has gone to the southern provinces, one to the south of rivers, one races through the capital's streets, and one keeps watch over an empty hall. Our scattering has reached its extreme. Next year, who knows where this body will be? Gathering must bring parting; parting must bring gathering. We cannot remain gathered forever, nor parted forever. Next year I may return, or may not; we may all reunite, or scatter again. Some force beyond our knowing moves these threads.

    Our fleeting lives in this world are like floating clouds in vast emptiness—gathering together in billows, then drifting apart and dissolving. Endless cycles of coming and going, until all returns to the great void. Alas, it is only endless transformation.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Daebang (帶方) refers to Namwon, a region in what is now South Korea.
  - key: ''
    value: The metaphor of a 'school of fish' (同隊魚) emphasizes both the close coordination and the natural, organic bond among the four friends.
  - key: ''
    value: The contrast between outer appearance (officials) and inner essence (humble scholars) reflects the Neo-Confucian ideal of cultivating both public duty and personal virtue.
